summary: Review | Killing Eve Season 1 is a wild but beautiful beast
title: Review | Killing Eve Season 1 is a wild but beautiful beast
body:
★★★★★

As someone with no cable, it is extremely difficult to be on the know with new entertainment. When Killing Eve first dropped, I knew better than to get excited as I couldn’t watch it until it came on a streaming service. Lo and behold, it did!

Adapted from Codename Villanelle by Luke Jennings by Phoebe Waller-Bridge, Killing Eve is, excuse my wording, delicious. Every episode is like a Bond movie - the big letters of cities with the gorgeous backdrops, the music with the sultry vocals, and the wide angle transition shots. Helmed by both old and new talent, respectively, Eve (Sandra Oh) and Villanelle (Jodie Comer) dance around each other with such force that it’s impossible to look away. 

In fact, that energy is what makes this show so sexy, and not the fact that it hints as a lesbian relationship (although, some scenes are hot as hell). It’s a game of cat and mouse between two badass characters who just happen to be female. Their genders are never used for the sake of the plot, and that is refreshing in its own right. Both Eve and Villanelle are intelligent, hilarious, and sport backbones that allow them to be as bold as they are. 

Oh as Eve is a force, but that is hardly a surprise. Although Eve is not the assassin, she is still just as crazy. She is obsessive and aggressive, and Oh captures this by her many facial expressions. Eve loves Villanelle but not romantically, and watching Oh makes you wonder if you yourself can trust her at all. Moreover, not only can she hold her own but she is also just funny as hell, the passcode scene being my particularly favorite. 

Comer on the other hand is a pleasant surprise. I had never heard of her before Killing Eve, and I must admit that I have a huge crush on her and her character. I know I know, Villanelle is a crazy psychobitch, but there is something about her and the way Comer seamlessly fills her shoes that are glorious. Villanelle is also almost childlike in the best way possible, and she loves fashion and food. If it weren’t for the killing part, I would totally date her. 

Season 1 was a rollercoaster, and one that I would ride over and over again. Tautly written and led by strong performances by the entire cast, Killing Eve is a sparkling gem. The last episode was a banger, and I am utterly breathtaken by how things ended: Will Villanelle go back on her promise and kill Eve? Will Eve stay in Paris and look for Villanelle or go back to London? If she goes back to London, what happens to the organization now that Carolyn Martens dissolved it? Speaking of Carolyn Martens, how does she know Villanelle? What did they talk about back in the prison? Will Eve create her own secret branch to continue investigating Villanelle? And perhaps the most mysterious: Who are the Twelve? 

Duration: 12/13/18 - 12/21/18

body: For some reason, I always had it in my head that season 2 of Killling Eve was going to be taking place at least a couple months after the season 1 finale. But unless there’s flashbacks, it looks like it’s gonna take place directly after it instead. (That promo pic of Villanelle wearing the same clothes she was stabbed in and appearing to be looking at her stomach wound). And….that’s interesting. Now i’m gonna have to re-think all of my theories of how the season is gonna go lol
